  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3434524891" />
    <a title="Bonnie Tharp" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/296872-bonnie-tharp"><img alt="Bonnie Tharp" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563123936p2/296872.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3434524891?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bonnie Tharp" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bonnie Tharp" href="/user/show/296872-bonnie-tharp">Bonnie Tharp</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3434524891" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer472115015156917347">I love Louis L&apos;Amour books, he&apos;s a great storyteller. This one was published after his death so I was a little disappointed that it wasn&apos;t edited more. The story idea was great, but there was a lot of internal monologues, repetition, and rambling that really slowed down things. He always wrote tight and kept me enthralled in his earlier works. The bonus material was interesting, his son did a lot of the location research. I&apos;m not sorry I read it, but it&apos;s not my favorite. If you like legends and</span>
  <span id="freeText472115015156917347" style="display:none">I love Louis L'Amour books, he's a great storyteller. This one was published after his death so I was a little disappointed that it wasn't edited more. The story idea was great, but there was a lot of internal monologues, repetition, and rambling that really slowed down things. He always wrote tight and kept me enthralled in his earlier works. The bonus material was interesting, his son did a lot of the location research. I'm not sorry I read it, but it's not my favorite. If you like legends and alternative worlds, you'll enjoy it. I did.</span>
  <a data-text-id="472115015156917347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

