<div id="review_543256029" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/543256029" />
    <a title="Foxfire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5312002-foxfire"><img alt="Foxfire" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/543256029?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Foxfire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Foxfire" href="/user/show/5312002-foxfire">Foxfire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer543256029" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11085087464065364707">Like so many others, I found this book too slow and repetitive. The hero is constantly mulling over the situation in his head, summarising the information the reader already knows. <br/><br/>Much of this is done in form of rhetorical questions as he contemplates the existence of a parallel world: What will be be like? What do I know? What do they know? Should I go? Will it be dangerous? <br/> <br/>It gets irritating after a while. <br/><br/>Also repeated are several philosophical passages about the tendency of mankind to fea</span>
  <span id="freeText11085087464065364707" style="display:none">Like so many others, I found this book too slow and repetitive. The hero is constantly mulling over the situation in his head, summarising the information the reader already knows. <br /><br />Much of this is done in form of rhetorical questions as he contemplates the existence of a parallel world: What will be be like? What do I know? What do they know? Should I go? Will it be dangerous? <br /> <br />It gets irritating after a while. <br /><br />Also repeated are several philosophical passages about the tendency of mankind to fear the unknown and cling to their established view of the world.<br /><br />The writing is clear and simple but falls a little flat. <br /><br />There is a fair bit of description, but it doesn't give me a clear idea of the surroundings, and never makes me feel I'm there. And it is repetitive. One page has: The night was cold. There were stars in the sky. One the next page: The night was cold. The stars were bright. A couple of pages later: The night was cold.<br /><br />In one scene, the sentence "He added fuel to the fire" is used four times, plus twice "He moved fuel closer to the fire".<br /><br />Once you spot these stock sentences used too frequently, they become distracting.<br /><br />It might have been a great story if not burdened by the endless repetition (or the continuity issues and minor plotholes others have pointed out, such as the dog and the icebox). </span>
  <a data-text-id="11085087464065364707" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


